metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #378
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash ‚Äî they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: the centre cannot hold #147
metadata.description:
The spiral is one of the earliest symbols used by humans, found in cave paintings and petroglyphs, and is thought by some researchers to have been inspired by shamanic rituals and hallucinogenic experiences. 

The spiral is found in our mathematics via the golden ratio, and in our aesthetics via the Fibonacci Spiral, aka the Golden Spiral. Spirals are found throughout the natural world, from the shape of our galaxy, to hurricane storms in our atmosphere, to seashells in the oceans.   

Spirals are also used to conceptualize entropy, spiraling out of control, the downward spiral from order into chaos. Each of these works represents this form of spiral, with varying degrees of chaos versus order, a formerly-cohesive group throwing off parts of itself due to overwhelming centrifugal force.   
--  
Uses p5js (LGPL-2.1). Color palettes are inspired by the paintings of Mondrian, Rafael, Van Gogh, Munch, O'Keefe, and Magritte.

metadata.name: lightscapes//linescapes//darkscapes #184
metadata.description:
A landscape made of monochromatic rows arranged by color to create an illusion of depth.

Each token comes with some fixed constraints, some constantly changing elements, and 3 possible styles.

The lightscape mode creates the most natural view, while the darkscape mode reveals the skeleton of the image. The linescape mode blends the two and looks a bit more like an illustration.

CONTROLS:
- click/tap on the image to regenerate and cycle through the different styles
- press 's' to download a png at the current resolution

Hope you like it,
Cino

metadata.name: Ries #113
metadata.description:
Ries is 500 sheets of paper. 
Ries is an cut-up text-artwork.
Ries is artwork generated by an algorithm based on seeded random numbers.
Ries is a digital artwork installed in 5 forms in exhibitions setting.
Ries is an NFT artwork. 

Ries is an artwork where I try bring together my experience of doing gallery exhibitions, my love for generative and copy machine art, DIY-punk aesthetics, NFT‚Äôs and chaos. 

The edition of Ries will be installed in different forms and collages in a gallery exhibition in Walden Kunstaustellungen in Berlin in July of 2022. Opening is at 8.7. 19.00, welcome if you are in Berlin.
/www.galerie-walden.de/

The seed idea for the project was the method of cut-up where a text (or something else) is cut into pieces and then rearranged to form something new. A modified Markov‚Äôs Chain algorithm makes a small text or a group of words from a pool of texts that include Art texts about cut up technique and generative art talk from tweets. These words form a visual bottom layer and then another layer of words samples the first, cutting it up and thus following the theme of the artwork.

Since the single iterations of the project are designed to be used in a collage, they come in various tone, density, detail and scale. One can test from the variations button and get a sense of what the generator produces. 

Controls in live view:
-Pressing  j exports the current image as jpeg
-Pressing  p  exports the current image as png

To change the detail level one can access the pixel density of render by adding ?pixDens=4 to the end of the URL in live view. You can of course you any number other than 4 also. I it renders just a black image, you have to lower the number, since it is then too large for WEBGL to render.

Designed to be best rendered on desktop Chrome.

Pricing info
22 tez - Includes a gallery shown, signed print sent to minter by mail or by telefax(!)
11 tez - A fair price for an artwork, also the minter can personally pick up a signed gallery shown print from the gallery, after the exhibition.
5 tez - 1/2 fair price
2 tez - bottom dollar

If you minted on lower tiers and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm to ‚Äúupgrade‚Äù. If you bought secondary, and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm.

Features exist mostly to help with artwork pairing for the collectors.


Markov‚Äôs chain code core is based on Markov Me! By https://codepen.io/alexkramerbanjo , MIT License

Displacement shader based on the wonderful shader examples by Adam Ferris


The artist holds the right to use the whole edition of Ries for display purposes for future exhibitions without asking permission or notifying the owners of the NFT‚Äôs.

metadata.name: Pulsar #114
metadata.description:
When exploring new possibilities for a new work, I stumbled across an article on Pulsar map. Created by astronomer Frank Drake and Carl Sagan, this map serves as a galactic address of our solar system for any extra-terrestrial civilization to find using pulsars as signposts. Though chances of any kind of life form intercepting the map are slim, I'm still fascinated both by the possibility of another planetary civilization finding the map (and by extension our Earth), and the thought of using pulsar -- the remaining corpse of ancient massive star -- as universal signposts and landmarks to map the Earth position for any kind of possible civilization. To me there's something so poetic about this; it made me thinks of how small are we, the Humans, compared to those rotating pulsars that we use as mere landmarks to our location...let alone the whole universe. We are just floating stardust after all.

In this piece I use Lissajous curve array with randomized variable to position the stars and generate spline as 'star trails'. The Lissajous array is interpolated with Perlin noise array to make it less smooth and looks more random.



----------
Control:
Press [s] to capture a screenshot of the current viewport.
Press [t] to toggle the star trails (default: enabled).



Made with Cables.gl

XALTED 2022
